## Project Motivation

Traditional memory games provide the same experience for every player by using fixed levels and predefined progression.

The goal of Memory was to create a system capable of analysing user behaviour and automatically adapting future training sessions, resulting in a more personalized and engaging cognitive training experience.

---

## Design Decisions

### Why adaptive difficulty?

Traditional memory games become repetitive because every player follows the same progression.

Memory dynamically adjusts the difficulty level according to the user's performance, making every training session unique.

### Why behaviour analysis?

Instead of evaluating only the final score, the application analyses how the player solves the game, allowing more accurate adaptation of future sessions.

### Why gamification?

Achievements, rewards, unlockable themes and progression mechanics increase long-term engagement and encourage regular cognitive training.

---

## Adaptive Cognitive Engine

The adaptive algorithm continuously analyses multiple variables during gameplay:

- completion time,
- player effectiveness,
- board configuration,
- previous sessions,
- gameplay strategy,
- mistake frequency,
- player progress.

Based on these factors, the application dynamically adjusts the next training session instead of relying on predefined progression.

```text
Player
   │
   ▼
Gameplay
   │
   ▼
Behaviour Analysis
   │
   ▼
Adaptive Algorithm
   │
   ▼
Difficulty Adjustment
   │
   ▼
Next Training Session
```

---

## Player Behaviour Analysis

Instead of treating every incorrect move equally, the application classifies different categories of mistakes:

- Cognitive mistakes
- Associative mistakes
- Spatial mistakes
- Attention mistakes

The application also recognises different playing strategies, reducing false classifications and improving the quality of behavioural analysis.

